<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-07-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-07-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="117" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.001 F35/–</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Minister</gloss> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 51</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-07-12">
                                    <hi rend="italic">July 12, 1917</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I am instructed by my Government to
                            communicate to you the following proclamation of the President of the
                            Republic of China: <pb facs="0253" n="87" xml:id="pg_87"/>
                            <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Whereas President Li Yuan Hung is unable, for cause, to perform
                                    the duties of his office;</p>
                                <p>Now, therefore, I, Feng Kuo-Chang, do hereby proclaim to all whom
                                    it may concern that in pursuance of Article 5, Section 2, of the
                                    Presidential Election Law, I have, on this 6th day of the 7th
                                    month (July 6, 1917), respectfully taken up the duties of the
                                    office of the President of the Republic.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">V. K. Wellington Koo</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>